segments.text: Well, let's see.
What were the benefits of being president of the student body?
You didn't get a scholarship.
Just the opportunity to work with some of the best on campus and the opportunity to get exposure to the other universities.
Those were the purposes.
Alright, as you look back on it, of what are you most proud from that year as student body president?
Or student senate president, I should say.
Probably our work with SCONA and with the other universities and having the opportunity to meet them.
We didn't have any major campus turmoil that we dealt with that stands out that I remember.
What was your impression of Earl Rudder then as the new president?
Well, he became president the year after I, he was vice president.
I knew him more as,
someone who we babysit for than someone who was president.
I know that there was a, at that time, concern over what kind of leadership he would provide not being an academician.
but surprised most people at the qualitative decisions.
A lot of the decisions, of course, weren't known even to the community, the faculty staff,
Things were run different back then.
Was it pretty clearly understood that he was going to become the president soon?
It was pretty clearly understood that he was boss.
Okay, that's what I, that's what I thought.
It didn't matter what you called him.
He made, he made many of the decisions that were important.
And that if you didn't agree with him, you needed to go to TU or SMU or TCU, somewhere else.
Different world.
There were no incidents that caused you and other student leaders to get called in and say, here's a problem, you all solve it?
No.
I don't ever remember visiting either the president's office or the vice president, any administrator's office.
We worked with Dean Penberthy on campus issues.
Who were the other key student leaders?
The corps commander.
Corps staff.
Don Cloud, as seniors, was the corps commander.
Gary Pepper was president of the senior class.
Joe Buescher was editor of the battalion.
Rod Stepp was the editor of the Aggieland.
These were people that you worked with on campus problems, solving them, that you saw frequently in meetings or sessions.
Let's see.
your whole four years give some examples of some good bulls, some pranks, some jokes that you were aware of.
Well, of course, the biggest activity were drowned outs, either where you would pick an individual, junior or senior, and in a few cases sophomores.
And there were certainly tricks of not getting caught and of doing the job extremely well.
Every now and then we had Babo bombs but not very often and usually two or three times a year usually during dead week just before finals in the fall and spring you'd have a
the whole core area around Duncan or around Speedy's, every dorm would get involved in these huge water fights.
The whole, everything.
Where would they take place?
Out there in the quadrangle in front of the dorms.
Throwing?
In the units, whenever you drowned somebody out, you'd drown them out in their room.
And usually that occurred when they had gone to sleep and you'd take about three freshmen with their waist back
waste baskets full of water and dump them and then lock the door so he couldn't get out.
So you'd dump it on him in bed?
In bed.
It wasn't one of these where you leaned it against the door?
No, no.

You dumped it on him and then you had someone with a fuck stick on the door and when you'd get out then they'd lock the door where he couldn't get out and you'd go back to your room and try to make sure that nobody could trace to who had done it.
But the dead week, we'd always have everybody would be involved.
I mean, water would be flying everywhere.
Most of it occurred out in the quadrangle rather than in the dorms.
But you'd have every faucet on that first floor running full steam and people in line to fill up wastebaskets.
Now, the Babbo bomb, was that normally rolled into the room, open the door and roll it in there?
Yeah.
Either that or they'd walk it in and light it in the room, depending on whether the individual was asleep or awake.
Okay.
Did you normally, was a Babel bomb used while the person was in the room?
Or did you ever do it?
Sometimes either way.
Sometimes you just ruin it.
Your objective was to really mess up the room.
Other times it was to get a rise out of the individual.
And you always were asleep.
You wouldn't do it if they were sitting up studying.
Did anybody ever put an animal in somebody else's room in your days?
Oh, yeah.
What?
That was the only situation for us old country boys had the upper hand on kids from Houston.

because they hadn't been around snakes and armadillos and the like and so there was a great deal of concern about how much damage one of those animals could do if you weren't really familiar with them so it was not uncommon to
put a snake in between the sheets.
What variety of snake?
Well, generally garden snakes because even though we were boastful, we weren't dumb.
We didn't have a rattlesnake.
I had a freshman, Ed Hill.
In fact, he worked down here before he passed away here about three years ago.
But Ed was a herpetology major, wildlife sciences major, and he kept snakes in gallon jars in his room.
And nothing was more exciting than for Ed to walk out in the hall and announce that he couldn't find his rattlesnake.
Everybody got bricks and put up beneath their doors where there wouldn't be any opening at all.
But we'd just take and slip those snakes in between the sheets.
and then just quietly wake, tried to not be observable till the light went out in the room and then just listen.
They'd always found that snake.
Sometimes it took a while for people to slide in bed before that snake moved or before they contacted.
But you could always tell the minute they realized what it was or that it was something.
Where would you all get the snakes?
No, they were all around out here on campus, Brightest River.
You'd just catch them.
And you mentioned armadillo.
Did they ever put an armadillo in somebody's room?
Yeah.
What else?
Those were the two primary targets with snakes and armadillos.
Did anybody ever put a cow or a sheep in anybody's room?
I'm sure that happened.
Not that I recall in our outfits.
Because I had one old-timer in one of the Northgate.
They put a cow in somebody's room on Friday, and it was there all weekend on the fourth floor.
And he said, you think it was hard getting that cow up.
Wait till you try to get that cow down, where the head shifts that center of gravity.
Let's see.
That was before elevators.
Yes, yes, yes.
In any dog.
Was there a fish day in your era?
We had a fish day that we were essentially to treat sophomores like freshmen and vice versa.
Describe how that went as you remember.
Well, we knew that that was only one day, so we never did get really wild about the treatment of sophomores.
It usually had to do with hitting braces and...

doing push-ups and simple stuff because we didn't have the opportunity to get even it never occurred because if you're a freshman the sophomores junior and senior were going to always be ahead of you now a year ahead of you was a young man named ray bowen yes he was over in the air force and i don't really remember ray except on student senate
He was a senior when I was a junior on the student center.
What kind of a student did he seem to be?
Ray was serious and he was an engineer so I didn't have a lot of contact with him and don't have a lot of memory other than I did remember Ray Bowen when it was announced that he was named president.
I had to go to my A-land to recall what he looked like.
Were there any other, you mentioned some, who were some of the student celebrities, people that would later become well-known that were here when you were?
Well, of course, Davis Ford was president of the association.
Bully Fernandez was president of the association.
He's my roommate.
You called Bully?
Well, Raul.
No, but no, but Bully?
Bully, yep.
That's what, I didn't know he had another name until we were out of school.
Where'd you get the Bully?
Can't tell you.
It came here with him.
Oh, really?
Okay, all right.
Whenever, he was Fish Fernandez for a year, and then he was Bully for three years.
And he was your roommate for?
Sophomore and junior year.
Right.
How were Hispanics treated during those years?
We didn't know the difference.
I didn't know what a Hispanic was.
I knew he was from Laredo.
I figured he was a little darker than I was because they got more sun down there.
But Bully was just another Aggie.
In general, describe the student body.
They were all male, but
They were from what kind of towns, what kind of families and income?
Probably over half of them came from small towns.
You still had a significant number of kids from Dallas, Fort Worth, and Houston.
Don't remember that many from San Antone, Austin.
Over half of our kids in our outfit were from small towns.
Bullets from Laredo, we had two kids from Mount Pleasant, from Wheeler, Wellington, three of the kids from Gatesville.
And most of them from parents that had not gone to college?
I would say the majority were.
Were?
Not college graduates.
Most of them came and
A bunch of them came, I mean they had no idea when they graduated from high school they were even going to college.
Many of them decided in August because they couldn't find a job or they couldn't find anything else to do or someone suggested that they might want to try A&M, just showed up at the door last August.
And what did you and your buddies assume were, in fact, the rules about classroom behavior?
I know there weren't any written rules, but what did y'all?
Well, I don't know that we ever thought about it because you went to class and you listened and the staff were kind of like mom and dad.
Did y'all ever do any pranks in class?
No.
Not until we got, until I became a graduate student, and then things loosened up some.
But there was a certain element of fear.
How often did you go to class?
How often did you go to class?
Every time it met.
Unless I had flu, we had a flu epidemic my sophomore year.
Did you go to Quack Shack?
Yeah, that's where the military science was.
Where was it?
Well, it was over in the old barracks on the north part of campus.
Describe it physically.
They were two-story barracks.
They were tar paper outside and wood holding the tar paper from falling in on itself.
And you had these wooden chairs with the arm where you set your books and did your note taking.
Who was the, do you remember the doctors?
Oh, you're talking about the hospital.
I'm talking about where military science was held.
Oh, no, no, no.
Okay.
Quack Shack was the hospital, so to speak, over at where they have the services building now.
And it was a two-story, I believe, brick building.
And I was over there probably twice the four years I was here.
I heard a lot of stories about it.
I didn't spend any time over at Black Shack.
Who was the doctor, do you remember?
Don't remember.
And you could, if you were sick enough, you could spend the night there.
Oh, yes.
They had probably 12 or 13 beds, and whenever a flu or something like that hit, you were taken care of in the dorm.
The COs and the first sergeant would go over and get medicine and bring it and distribute it.
Your...

fish your sophomore buddies would bring food to the dorm from the mess hall and in a week you'd either die or get well but it it wasn't a large place that could handle a lot of people and I can remember the two times that I can remember going over there of spending well over an hour sitting and waiting to see anyone
So, it was, it wasn't a place that you couldn't wait until the next time to go back.
Alright.
Now, during these four busy years for you, did you continue to work?
Yes.
How much?
How many hours?
About 20 hours during the summers, during the terms of fall and spring, and then full time in the summer.
In entomology?
Yes.
Worked at the lab for two years, and then I, in 1957, was hired as extension entomologist at Lubbock.
Guy Carpenter, who was the area entomologist out there, was killed in a airplane.
Right, now you're doing this in the summer and then come back?

I was located in the basement of the AG building on the Tech campus where the district office was and worked with the county agents and the whole High Plains and Rolling Plains area on cotton insects primarily, wrote a newsletter.
Here on campus, how much did your pay
increased during those four years?
I think about 75 cents is what I made when I was a senior.
From 17 cents to about 75 cents.
The thing that I learned later when I went to work full-time, now I just worked summers as extension neurologist out there.
Danes used me just to fill in during the heat of the cotton season.
That's when everybody was under pressure.
but I got my first full-time job as extension entomologist area entomologist at Lubbock June 1 of 1960 and I didn't know it until I my dad passed away and I was going through some of his records and
I was hired for more than he made and he was working for the same organization and had been for 20 something years, since 42, and this was in 1960, 28 years.
And what was your starting pay?
Six thousand dollars, 500 a month, which I thought was just unheard of.
And we got
Three cents a mile for a mileage, and our per dime for our lodging and meals was six dollars a day.
Sounds like a cushy deal.
That's right.
But you know, we got by.
Now, let's back up.
Did you meet a special young lady during your student days here?
I met a bunch of them.
Met my wife.
I had known her, but we had not dated in high school.
And she was at OCW, and we started dating when I was a junior here at A&M.
And then she transferred to TU.
Okay.
And how would you visit with her after she gets to Austin?
About once a month.
Well, of course, in the fall, football game.

she would come over here sometimes with friends of hers that were in the same dorm and sometimes on a bus and that was an experience I understand I never rode the bus but there was a bus that went from Austin down through the bottom through Brenham and

all the country roads and as I understand it was driven by a fellow that had grown up down here in the Bravis bottoms and enjoyed telling people about every tree and every historical site and even would stop at his house and go in and have his supper and then come back out and finish the trip.
When you were dating this special young lady, where would y'all go on Friday and Saturday nights here?
There were activities here.
There wasn't any place, but if it was a football game, we went to the football game.
There was usually some kind of a dance or activity at the MSC after it.
And that's where we went.
Alright, if you wanted to go somewhere after the dance,
to eat, to have refreshments where?
That was very simple.
There was Zarape's, if you wanted Mexican food, and there was Werman's.
Zarape's was over here east of the campus near the water tower.
There used to be a water tower there.
Werman's was downtown Bryan, had chicken fried steaks.
And then there was a seafood place over on Old College, and I can't recall what the name of that.
Were there any places that young people might have gone that were a little bit on the edge of respectability?
I'm sure there were.
Was Uncle Ed's still going?
Yes, Uncle Ed's existed.
I had never been to Uncle Ed's, so I don't know whether that was a place that you just went and got beer like across the Bryce River Bridge.
So you didn't take your date there?
I had never been there.
Did you ever go to Whiskey Bridge across the?
I knew where it was because that's where I work.
Entomology had experiments down there, so I'd always pass it just as you went across the bridge on your right.
What did it look like from there?
It looked like an old shack.
And as far as you know, what did they sell other than whiskey?
As far as I knew, that's all they sold.
It wasn't a convenience store, was it, where you could buy bread and bologna?
No, no.
I never was in there.
Because it was still, when we got here, it was still there.
I was trying to remember when Arnold's was built.
I have eaten at Arnold's.
in that old red brick building.
I think it was here during that time.
Barbecue.
But they couldn't handle it about eight at one time, I think, if you sit down.
All right, did you and your buddies ever go to the clay pits swimming?
No, but we went to the river, Brass River.
That's where they would have beer bus units.
Describe that.
Well, they'd just get a bunch of beer and ice it down, and we'd go out there and raise hell.
And how would you all get there?
Usually two or three people would have vehicles.
And you'd fill it up with a... Everybody would pile in the back end of a truck.
And would there be any females in the group?
And what did they wear when they went swimming?
Nothing.
Their underwear.
So they would wear their skivvies?
Some wore underwear.
And some skinny dipped?
Yeah.
How drunk did people get?
Some of them had to be carried back.
Was there care given to who was the driver on the road back?
Yes.
We had designated drivers.
But you didn't use that phrase then.
No, there were people who didn't drink.
And this would happen normally on a?
Saturday?
Usually a Friday night.
A Friday night, okay.
Because football games were Saturday, and nearly always it was a Friday night, at least our outfit.
Let's see.
MSC, what role did the MSC play in a student's life during those years?
It was the only place that had activities, a piano, bowling alley.
It
I don't know what the Y used to be like.
In fact, I've never seen the swimming pool supposedly in the basement of the Y.
Did have those B meetings at the Y.
But the MSC was the living room of campus.
Everything happened there because you didn't have other options of places to go and the campus theater was where movies were shown and the MSC is where everything else happened.
Now did a student goof off, play tricks, act up in the MSC?
No.
That was strictly done in your room or in the core area.
And by your day, the YMCA was not a very significant student activity center.
Not at all.
The MSC, I think, opened probably about 51 or 52, and it was well established, and it was air conditioned.
What about...
That's what most people remember about the MSC.
It was the only cool place on campus.
And by and large, sophomores did not pick on freshmen in the MSC, did they?
No.
Wasn't that kind of an often?
That was a given.
in the MSC that everybody was, you still spoke, you still hit a brace, that just happened naturally, but there was no, essentially no hazing on the MSC.
Now Guyon Hall, what did you all go to Guyon Hall for?

Well that was where all of your other activities, that's where you had campus wide meetings, that's where the president would address all of the students, they would have plays there, they would bring in entertainment,
Do you remember any important entertainers during your four years?
Not really.
We didn't have those activities, but maybe one a year.
Let's see, Eisenhower's visit is not during your years, is it?
No, it was a little later.
No important politics.
What about Scona?
Did you all have some notable...

speakers they were at that point in time notable you recognize the names as people who were in the military in politics or in big business at this time I couldn't tell you who was there in our freshman through senior years I remember during
my early years of being a Skona advisor, we had Senator Albert Gore of Tennessee.
Well, he has a relationship with the present day.
Yes, I don't remember his mentioning a son at all when he was here.
Let's see, did you go to movies in Gine Hall?
Yes, on Saturdays and probably Sundays.
Were you all shown We've Never Been Licked?
It showed several times.
And what did you and your buddies think of it?
Well, we were impressed.
It was a good movie.
Academically, were there any cush courses that people took just for grade points, easy courses?
Yeah, there were some that had the reputation of being easy courses.
What were they?
Did you all talk about Dr. Dan, the grade point man?
I've heard that phrase.
I couldn't even tell you where he taught.
Dan Russell, rural sociology.
Rural sociology.
What courses did athletes take?
Were there supposedly some?
I assume that they took the same courses we did, but I don't recall that.
All right, and you were here during the Bear Bryant years.
Right.
He was in his second year here in the fall of 55 when we came.
He'd been here one year.
What impression did Bear Bryant make on you students?
He wasn't very sociable.
He had breakfast every morning at 6 over there at that drugstore.
At Southgate?
At Northgate.
Oh, at Northgate.
Right where Lupo's is now, but there was a drug store on that corner.
And he would come in and they would always have a paper and there was one seat that was, quote, his.
Nobody, if you sat there, you were asked to move that this is Coach Bryant's.

He would come in, pick up the paper, they knew what he wanted, they'd bring his breakfast over, and he would sit there and drink coffee, and you could walk right up to him and say, howdy, and you didn't exist.
He was, as a student, and as I remember it, he was very unfriendly.
Were you acquainted with any of the famous members of the football team?
Who were some of them?
Ma Hamilton served meals, family style.
And I don't know if it was suggested or recommended that they eat over there, but Krueger, John David Crowe, Murray Trimble,
who was one-armed, ate their supper there.
Ma Hamilton was a real small lady.
She probably was 4'6", 4'7", very spirited.
But after eating, I can remember they would, I don't know whether it was their responsibility or they just enjoyed it or if it was fun for them, but they would wash dishes.
One of them beat the sink washing dishes and the cupboard was on the other side of the kitchen.
And they would throw the glasses and the plates across the room until Ma came back.
So one would wash, one would rinse, and one would dry.
